<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=362611203&t=artid%3d80592f88-9fda-4c65-a936-d6de96fd883e%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=362611203&t=artid%3d80592f88-9fda-4c65-a936-d6de96fd883e%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>Dhlomo said breast and cervical cancer are two of the most common cancers affecting South African women today. “It’s due to early detection of breast cancer that many women are still alive. “We want to have a situation where in the next 10 years the only cancer we talk about is cervical cancer because it’s able to hide itself.”Dhlomo said it’s unlike breast cancer which is much easier to detect.He said women should regularly examine their breasts. “Stand in front of a mirror, lift your hands and observe if both breasts go up. If one of them doesn’t then it’s a sign something may be wrong. That’s when you visit a health facility,” he said.Dhlomo also said cervical cancer mostly affects women in their 30s. “It used to affect mostly older women in their 60s. The National Council has formulated the National Cervical Cancer Prevention Policy and the Breast Cancer Prevention Policy to ensure early symptoms are identified.” A resident, Nosipho Nxasana (39), said: “Cancer is painful but if it’s detected early, it can be treated. I will start doing regular check-ups with the help of my partner, as the MEC has said.”. 
